<HEADLINE>
<P>
METALLIC BALLOONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Recently, while driving south on the Harbor Freeway between Imperial and 
Rosecrans, I saw a group of about five metallic balloons tied together floating 
above. They came to rest to the west of the freeway on power lines, at which 
time a series of flashes ensued. 
</P>
<P>
As a result, two or three (possibly more) of these power lines were severed and 
fell earthward. 
</P>
<P>
The balloon manufacturer has made its profit and the public collectively shares 
in the costly repair. 
</P>
<P>
Of course this pales in comparison with the scenario whereby lives are 
endangered due to dangling live wires. 
</P>
<P>
Metallic balloons are not an essential to our quality of life, and as a result 
of my experience, I cannot imagine reason enough for their continued existence. 
</P>
<P>
DIANE McDOWELL 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
