<HEADLINE>
<P>
4 RESCUED AFTER THEIR SMALL PLANE CRASHES INTO SEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four people were rescued from the waters off Rancho Palos Verdes on Sunday 
after their light airplane crashed into the sea, the Redondo Beach Harbor 
Patrol said. 
</P>
<P>
The crew of a charter whale-watching boat pulled the four victims from the 
water minutes after the single-engine Bellanca aircraft crashed about 3:50 
p.m., said Harbor Patrol spokesman Officer Kevin McCamy. 
</P>
<P>
The victims -- two men, a woman and a 12-year-old girl -- were treated for 
minor cuts and bruises at South Bay Hospital and released, McCamy said. Their 
names were not released. 
</P>
<P>
McCamy said the four-seat plane, which was returning to Santa Monica from Santa 
Catalina Island, went down after its fuel pump and a back-up pump both 
malfunctioned. 
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately, the plane landed on its belly," McCamy said. "They got a 
relatively good landing. They were able to gather their things and get into the 
water." 
</P>
<P>
After the victims discovered that the plane was temporarily buoyant, McCamy 
said, they scrambled out of the water and onto the wings of the aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
Moments later, the crew of the whale-watching vessel Voyager arrived and helped 
the stranded foursome aboard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
