</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WATER SKIER, 26, KILLED BY BOAT THAT TOWED HIM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIC LICHTBLAU, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEWPORT BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 26-year-old water skier was fatally injured Sunday afternoon when he was run 
over by a boat that had been towing him, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Louis Michael Andreoli of Newport Beach was pronounced dead at 2:09 p.m., less 
than an hour after the boating mishap in which he suffered head injuries, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
Andreoli had gone water skiing with three friends in a borrowed, 18-foot 
inboard-outboard power boat Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
He was skiing about 400 yards offshore from the main Corona del Mar beach 
Sunday afternoon when, "for some reason, he was run over by his friends," said 
Lt. Don Chandler of the Newport Beach Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
Chandler said the boat was impounded and the case is under investigation. He 
refused to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
Lt. William Francis of the Orange County Sheriff's Department, which responded 
to the incident, said: "We're satisfied that it's strictly a boating accident. 
There's nothing to indicate there was anything intentional, absolutely 
nothing." 
</P>
<P>
Francis declined further comment. 
</P>
<P>
Chandler said he could remember few if any fatalities like the one Sunday. And 
Sgt. Howard Mol of the Sheriff's Harbor Patrol, while recalling some serious 
jet-ski accidents, said: "This is really the first fatal water-skiing accident 
in at least four years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Newport beach firefighters and paramedics minister to Louis Michael 
Andreoli, 26, who died after being hit by boat off Corona del Mar beach. 
RICHARD KOEHLER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
