<HEADLINE>
<P>
'RAINMAKER' BECK LEFT TRAIL OF LIES -- REPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Investment banker Jeffrey Beck, who helped negotiate some of the biggest 
takeovers of the 1980s, continually lied about his past, fabricating stories 
about his background and military service and claiming to work for the Central 
Intelligence Agency, a published report said today. 
</P>
<P>
Beck, a member of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s mergers and acquisitions 
department, allegedly told friends and colleagues over the years that he had 
served in the Army's Special Forces in Vietnam, that he did intelligence work 
for the U.S. government and that he would inherit a family fortune of $2 
billion, the Wall Street Journal reported. 
</P>
<P>
However, the newspaper said after interviewing friends, family, colleagues and 
acquaintances of the investment banker, none of the stories apparently was 
true. Drexel and Oppenheimer &amp; Co., which was Beck's previous employer, 
kept him in their mergers and acquisitions departments although many of his 
co-workers did not believe his stories, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
Beck could not immediately be reached today to comment on the story; his office 
said he was out. 
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that during an interview Beck backtracked on some of his 
prior claims, categorically denying that he had told most of the stories 
attributed to him by what the newspaper called business associates, friends and 
others. 
</P>
<P>
"This is getting wilder and wilder," he told the newspaper. "I am beyond 
shock." 
</P>
<P>
Beck acknowledged there were no official records of his Vietnam service, but 
said he had made trips to Vietnam, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
The article also said Beck claimed he had done years of intelligence work, but 
denied having told people he worked for the CIA or that he would inherit a 
$2-billion fortune. 
</P>
<P>
Beck, nicknamed "Mad Dog," is a "rainmaker," one who drums up takeover business 
for investment firms. He has been highly successful, working as an adviser to 
the buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. on a number of deals, 
including its record $24.53-billion purchase of RJR Nabisco Inc. in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
