<P>
TOYOTA EXPORTS OFF, NISSAN'S UP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan's leading car makers, Toyota and Nissan, today reported mixed results in 
exports for 1989, with Toyota's exports declining 8.1% from the previous year 
and Nissan posting its first rise in four years. 
</P>
<P>
Toyota cited sluggish exports to the United States as the main reason for its 
drop. 
</P>
<P>
Toyota, Japan's No. 1 car maker, said total exports for 1989 were down 8.1% to 
1,669,130 units -- the first time in two years that total exports fell below 
those of the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
Nissan's exports for 1989 amounted to 1,064,172 units, an increase of 2% over 
the year before. "This increase in exports reflects 1988's low figure and the 
favorable reception of new Nissan models in the U.S. market," the company said. 
</P>
<P>
Both Tokyo and Nissan reported record domestic vehicle sales in 1989 amid 
booming domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
